sentences: Luis Eduardo Aute was born in Manila on 13 September 1943.

sentences: His father, a Catalan (from Catalonia, Spain) worked there for a tobacco company since 1919 and married a Spanish Filipina.

sentences: In 1954, after a short stay in Barcelona, Aute returned definitively to Madrid, where he studied at the Colegio Nuestra Señora de las Maravillas.
His first album was Diálogos de Rodrigo y Ximena in 1968.
By the 1970s, he was creating soundtracks for films directed by Jaime Chávarri, Luis García Berlanga, Fernando Fernán-Gómez, Fernando Méndez, and others.
In 1977, Aute performed in his first large public concert in Spain.
Aute had his first individual exhibit in the gallery Alcon de Madrid in 1960.
By 1964, his work was being sold in the United States at the Juarez Gallery in Palm Beach, Florida.
In 1966, he was selected to participate in the Nona Biennial de São Paulo in Brazil, where he brought three large pieces.
In 1974, Aute won first prize for painting in the XXVIII Mostra Michetti in Italy.
In 1961, he created Senses, a short film.
In 1970, he wrote and directed another short film, Minutos después, which was selected for the II festival de Cine de Autor de Benalmádena.
In 1974 he wrote and directed A flor de piel, his last short film for over ten years.

Although he'd written poetry in both English and Spanish as a youth, Aute made a big splash in 1970 when he published a poem and drawing in Poesia 70 that managed to get the magazine shut down in conservative, Franco-controlled Spain.
In 1975, he publishedLa matemática del espejo and followed it up a year later with "Songs and Poems."
In 1978, he published La liturgia del desorden.
In 1980, Aute began a long musical association with Luis Mendo, who arranged many of his songs.
In 1983, Aute performed in a concert, "Entre Amigos", with Silvio Rodríguez, Pablo Milanés, Teddy Bautista, and Joan Manuel Serrat.
In 1984, he released "Cuerpo a cuerpo", the first time he combined his music and art thematically.
In 1992, "Slowly" climbed the charts and was followed one year later by Mano a Mano with Silvio Rodriguez.
In the 1980s, Aute's work was exhibited in galleries and shows all over Europe.
In 1987, he combined an album, "Templo", with an art exhibit.
In 1986, Aute wrote and directed El muro de las lamentaciones; it was followed by La pupila del éxtasis, several years later.
In 1980, he put out a revised edition of Songs and Poems.
In 2000, a number of Aute's peers produced a tribute album called "Mira que eres canalla, Aute" as a tribute to him.
In 2001, he was awarded the Premio Luigi Tenco for his body of work.
In 2003, he released Alas and Balas, his first album in four years and "Auterretratos," a collection of his work that was completed later with "Auterretratos Volumes Two and Three."
In 2012, he released El niño que miraba el mar, an animated film, scored by Aute himself, that also featured his own drawings.
In 2015, Aute released Canciones de Amor y Destrucción, an album he combined with 3D art work and toured with Giraluna, a concert featuring a short film animated and produced by Aute.
He also toured with an exhibit called "Transfiguraciones" that had venues in Cuba, Spain, Colombia, Ecuador, and Italy between 2004 and 2010.
Rarely has a year gone by since his first exhibit in 1960 without an Aute show somewhere in the world.
In 2001, Aute released Un perro llamado Dolor, an animated film that he wrote, directed, and scored.
In 2002, Aute released "Volver al agua," a compilation of his work.
This was followed by "What Things Are" in 2005.

Fifteen years later, another generation of musicians released a second tribute, Giraluna.
The 21st century brought a new twist to his work with a film called Un perro llamado Dolor.
He followed this pattern with a successful tour of Latin America and Spain with an exhibit called Ad Libidum in the mid 1990s.

sentences: At 15, with his new guitar received as a birthday present, he performed at an end of school party, as part of a trio with two friends.
During these early years he was strongly influenced by German Expressionism and dedicated most of his time to painting, winning a silver medal in a Spanish Juvenile Art Contest.
Aute spent more than a year in France after his military service in Catalan, working mainly in film.
When he returned to Spain, he began writing songs for other artists like Massiel (Rosas en el mar).
Invited by the Cuban government to participate in the World Festival of Youth in Havana, Aute contracted tuberculosis and spent five months in Cuba recovering.
Two years later, he had his second exhibit in Madrid's Gallery Quixote.
In 1974 he wrote and directed A flor de piel, his last short film for over ten years.
In 1975, he publishedLa matemática del espejo and followed it up a year later with "Songs and Poems."
In 1992, "Slowly" climbed the charts and was followed one year later by Mano a Mano with Silvio Rodriguez.
In 1986, Aute wrote and directed El muro de las lamentaciones; it was followed by La pupila del éxtasis, several years later.
Six years later, he released "Templo de carne".
In 2003, he released Alas and Balas, his first album in four years and "Auterretratos," a collection of his work that was completed later with "Auterretratos Volumes Two and Three."
In 2012, he released El niño que miraba el mar, an animated film, scored by Aute himself, that also featured his own drawings.
Rarely has a year gone by since his first exhibit in 1960 without an Aute show somewhere in the world.
